import arcpy
import os

#set workspace
arcpy.env.workspace = r"C:\Users\gandiaye\Downloads\2023-24 Classes\EAS 544\geotasks\task3\geotask3"
arcpy.env.overwriteOutput = True

#initialize lists for food and radii codes
foodList = ["fas", "oth", "ram", "eth", "far", "frm", "gro", "spc", "spm"]
radii = [805, 1609, 4828, 8047]

#initialize list that raster outputs will go into 
rasterList = []

#define inputs for kernel density
in_features = "foodpts.shp"
cell_size = 100 
out_workspace = r"C:\Users\gandiaye\Downloads\2023-24 Classes\EAS 544\geotasks\task3\geotask3\geotask3.gdb"

#iterate through food code and radii list
#for every food code, run a kernel density that calculates 
#the density of that food type given a certain radius
for foo in foodList:
    for rad in radii:
        print(foo, rad)
        population_field = foo #set the field to be calcualted on as the current food code
        searchRadius = radii #set the radius
        outKernelDensity = arcpy.sa.KernelDensity(in_features, foo, cell_size, 
        rad, "SQUARE_MILES", "DENSITIES", "PLANAR")
        new_out_workspace= out_workspace + "/"+ foo + str(rad) #concatenate the pathway and the current food code and radius to create a file pathway
        rasterList.append(new_out_workspace) #add this new kernel density to the raster list
        print(new_out_workspace)
        outKernelDensity.save(new_out_workspace)


arcpy.CheckOutExtension("Spatial") #checkin license

#Sample tool extracts the values from each raster dataset at the locations of the point features in the flint shapefile
arcpy.sa.Sample(rasterList, "flpeop.shp", r"C:\Users\gandiaye\Downloads\2023-24 Classes\EAS 544\geotasks\task3\geotask3\geotask3.gdb")
